WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.320
This is a LibriVox recording.

00:04.060 --> 00:07.240
All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:08.780 --> 00:16.100
For more information or to volunteer, please go to LibriVox.org.

00:16.960 --> 00:19.740
Recorded by Ife Currid.

00:20.580 --> 00:24.020
Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen.

00:24.420 --> 00:26.880
Chapters 46 and 47.

00:28.380 --> 00:29.500
Chapter 46.

00:31.860 --> 00:35.980
Elizabeth had been a good deal disappointed in not finding a letter from Jane on their

00:35.980 --> 00:41.800
first arrival at Lambdon, and this disappointment had been renewed on each of the mornings that

00:41.800 --> 00:47.700
had now been spent there, but on the third her repining was over and her sister justified

00:47.700 --> 00:53.840
by the receipt of two letters from her at once, on one of which was marked that it had

00:53.840 --> 00:55.240
been missent elsewhere.

00:56.160 --> 01:01.720
Elizabeth was not surprised at it, as Jane had written the direction remarkably ill.

01:03.120 --> 01:08.760
They had just been preparing to walk as the letters came in, and her uncle and aunt, leaving

01:08.760 --> 01:12.000
her to enjoy them in quiet, set off by themselves.

01:12.840 --> 01:18.020
The one missent must first be attended to, it had been written five days ago.

01:18.720 --> 01:23.980
The beginning contained an account of all their little parties and engagements, with

01:23.980 --> 01:30.180
such news as the country afforded, but the latter half, which was dated a day later and

01:30.180 --> 01:34.760
written in evident agitation, gave more important intelligence.

01:35.520 --> 01:36.980
It was to this effect.

01:38.320 --> 01:44.700
Since writing the above, dearest Lizzie, something has occurred of a most unexpected and serious

01:44.700 --> 01:49.720
nature, but I am afraid of alarming you, be assured that we are all well.

01:50.490 --> 01:52.860
What I have to say relates to poor Lydia.

01:53.620 --> 01:59.040
An express came at twelve last night, just as we were all gone to bed, from Colonel Forster,

01:59.540 --> 02:04.600
to inform us that she was gone off to Scotland with one of his officers, to own the truth

02:04.600 --> 02:05.680
with Wickham.

02:06.360 --> 02:07.740
Imagine our surprise!

02:08.400 --> 02:11.840
To Kitty, however, it does not seem so wholly unexpected.

02:12.480 --> 02:19.280
I am very, very sorry, so imprudent a match on both sides, but I am willing to hope the

02:19.280 --> 02:22.120
best, and that his character has been misunderstood.

02:22.920 --> 02:29.060
Thoughtless and indiscreet, I can easily believe him, but this step, and let us rejoice over

02:29.060 --> 02:31.500
it, marks nothing bad at heart.

02:32.000 --> 02:37.300
His choice is disinterested at least, for he must know my father can give her nothing.

02:37.940 --> 02:40.100
Our poor mother is sadly grieved.

02:40.520 --> 02:42.200
My father bears it better.

02:42.900 --> 02:47.000
How thankful I am that we never let them know what has been said against him.

02:47.600 --> 02:49.480
We must forget it ourselves.

02:50.580 --> 02:55.820
They were off Saturday night about twelve, as is conjectured, but were not missed till

02:55.820 --> 02:57.440
yesterday morning at eight.

02:58.060 --> 03:00.080
The express was sent off directly.

03:00.560 --> 03:04.560
My dear Lizzy, they must have passed within ten miles of us.

03:05.120 --> 03:08.380
Colonel Forster gives us reason to expect him here soon.

03:09.120 --> 03:13.140
Lydia left a few lines for his wife, informing her of their intention.

03:13.540 --> 03:16.780
I must conclude, for I cannot be long for my poor mother.

03:17.320 --> 03:21.560
I am afraid you will not be able to make it out, but I hardly know what I have written.

03:23.560 --> 03:30.120
Without allowing herself time for consideration, and scarcely knowing what she felt, Elizabeth,

03:30.360 --> 03:35.240
on finishing this letter, instantly seized the other, and opening it with the utmost

03:35.240 --> 03:37.280
impatience, read as follows.

03:37.680 --> 03:41.220
It had been written a day later than the conclusion of the first.

03:42.300 --> 03:46.800
By this time, my dearest sister, you have received my hurried letter.

03:47.600 --> 03:52.860
I wish this may be more intelligible, but though not confined for time, my head is so

03:52.860 --> 03:55.580
bewildered that I cannot answer for being coherent.

03:56.300 --> 04:01.440
Dearest Lizzy, I hardly know what I would write, but I have bad news for you, and it

04:01.440 --> 04:02.340
cannot be delayed.

04:03.260 --> 04:08.600
Imprudent as the marriage between Mr. Wickham and our poor Lydia would be, we are now anxious

04:08.600 --> 04:14.080
to be assured it has taken place, for there is but too much reason to fear they are not

04:14.080 --> 04:14.960
gone to Scotland.

04:15.560 --> 04:20.820
Colonel Forster came yesterday, having left Brighton the day before, not many hours after

04:20.820 --> 04:21.640
the express.

04:22.280 --> 04:26.540
Though Lydia's short letter to Mrs. F gave them to understand that they were going to

04:26.540 --> 04:32.980
Gretna Green, something was dropped by Denny expressing his belief that W never intended

04:32.980 --> 04:39.760
or to marry Lydia at all, which was repeated to Colonel F, who, instantly taking the alarm,

04:40.220 --> 04:42.880
set off from B intending to trace their route.

04:43.360 --> 04:49.740
He did trace them easily to Clapham, but no further, for on entering that place they removed

04:49.740 --> 04:53.680
into a hackney coach and dismissed the shades that brought them from Epsom.

04:54.440 --> 04:58.740
All that is known after this that they were seen to continue the London road.

04:59.080 --> 05:00.780
I know not what to think.

05:01.440 --> 05:07.280
After making every possible enquiry on that side London, Colonel F came on into Hertfordshire,

05:07.640 --> 05:12.860
anxiously renewing them at all the turnpikes and at the inns in Barnet and Hatfield, but

05:12.860 --> 05:14.080
without any success.

05:14.500 --> 05:16.980
No such people had been seen to pass through.

05:17.700 --> 05:23.080
With the kindest concern he came on to Longbourn and broke his apprehensions to us in a manner

05:23.080 --> 05:24.800
most creditable to his heart.

05:24.800 --> 05:30.820
I am sincerely grieved for him and Mrs F, but no one can throw any blame on them.

05:31.360 --> 05:34.500
Our distress, my dear Lizzie, is very great.

05:34.940 --> 05:39.180
My father and mother believe the worst, but I cannot think so ill of him.

05:39.820 --> 05:44.800
Many circumstances might make it more eligible for them to be married privately in town than

05:44.800 --> 05:46.280
to pursue their first plan.

05:46.780 --> 05:52.660
And even if he could form such a design against a young woman of Lydia's connections, which

05:52.660 --> 05:56.620
is not likely, can I suppose her soul lost to everything?

05:57.560 --> 05:58.160
Impossible!

05:58.840 --> 06:04.760
I grieve to find, however, that Colonel F is not disposed to depend upon their marriage.

06:05.220 --> 06:10.980
He shook his head when I expressed my hopes and said he feared W was not a man to be trusted.

06:11.780 --> 06:14.900
My poor mother is really ill and keeps her room.

06:15.520 --> 06:19.720
Could she exert herself it would be better, but this is not to be expected.

06:19.720 --> 06:24.340
And as to my father, I never in my life saw him so affected.

06:25.000 --> 06:29.960
Poor Kitty has anger for having concealed their attachment, but as it was a matter of

06:29.960 --> 06:31.580
confidence one cannot wonder.

06:32.240 --> 06:37.120
I am truly glad, dearest Lizzie, that you have been spared something of these distressing

06:37.120 --> 06:37.620
scenes.

06:37.940 --> 06:42.140
But now, as the first shock is over, I shall own that I long for your return.

06:42.840 --> 06:46.420
I am so selfish, however, as to press for it, if inconvenient.

06:47.220 --> 06:47.740
Adieu!

06:48.380 --> 06:54.180
I take up my pen again to do what I have just told you I would not, but circumstances are

06:54.180 --> 06:58.480
such that I cannot help earnestly begging you all to come here as soon as possible.

06:59.160 --> 07:04.120
I know my dear uncle and aunt so well that I am not afraid of requesting it, though I

07:04.120 --> 07:06.360
have still something more to ask of the former.

07:07.040 --> 07:12.480
My father is going to London with Colonel Forster instantly to try to discover her.

07:12.480 --> 07:18.480
What he means to do I am sure I know not, but his excessive distress will not allow

07:18.480 --> 07:23.840
him to pursue any measure in the best and safest way, and Colonel Forster is obliged

07:23.840 --> 07:25.980
to be at Brighton again tomorrow evening.

07:26.920 --> 07:31.780
In such an exigence, my uncle's advice and assistance would be everything in the world.

07:32.240 --> 07:36.780
He will immediately comprehend what I must feel, and I rely upon his goodness.

07:38.480 --> 07:41.120
Oh, where, where is my uncle?

07:41.620 --> 07:46.160
cried Elizabeth, darting from her seat as she finished the letter, in eagerness to

07:46.160 --> 07:49.140
follow him without losing a moment of the time so precious.

07:49.720 --> 07:54.840
But as she reached the door, it was opened by a servant, and Mr. Darcy appeared.

07:55.500 --> 07:58.760
Her pale face and impetuous manner made him start.

07:59.400 --> 08:05.460
And before he could recover himself to speak, she, in whose mind every idea was superseded

08:05.460 --> 08:08.400
by Lydia's situation, hastily exclaimed,

08:09.280 --> 08:11.600
I beg your pardon, but I must leave you.

08:11.680 --> 08:15.880
I must find Mr. Gardiner this moment, a business that cannot be delayed.

08:16.200 --> 08:17.860
I have not an instant to lose.

08:18.920 --> 08:20.900
Good God, what is the matter?

08:21.360 --> 08:24.060
cried he, with more feeling than politeness.

08:25.280 --> 08:26.940
Then, recollecting himself,

08:27.480 --> 08:32.880
I will not detain you a minute, but let me, or let the servant, go after Mr. and Mrs.

08:33.080 --> 08:33.440
Gardiner.

08:33.440 --> 08:37.580
You are not well enough, you cannot go yourself.

08:38.740 --> 08:42.060
Elizabeth hesitated, but her knees trembled under her,

08:42.240 --> 08:46.240
and she felt how little would be gained by her attempting to pursue them.

08:46.840 --> 08:50.180
Calling back the servant, therefore, she commissioned him,

08:50.300 --> 08:54.500
though in so breathless an accent as made her almost unintelligible,

08:55.000 --> 08:57.760
to fetch his master and mistress home instantly.

08:59.440 --> 09:03.420
On his quitting the room, she sat down, unable to support herself.

09:03.440 --> 09:08.740
And looking so miserably ill that it was impossible for Darcy to leave her,

09:08.920 --> 09:13.260
or to refrain from saying, in a tone of gentleness and commiseration,

09:14.260 --> 09:15.460
Let me call your maid.

09:15.980 --> 09:18.940
Is there nothing you could take to give you present relief?

09:19.400 --> 09:20.460
A glass of wine?

09:20.840 --> 09:21.840
Shall I get you one?

09:22.260 --> 09:23.800
You are very ill.

09:24.540 --> 09:28.960
No, I thank you, she replied, endeavouring to recover herself.

09:29.740 --> 09:31.560
There is nothing the matter with me.

09:31.560 --> 09:32.880
I am quite well.

09:32.880 --> 09:37.360
I am only distressed by some dreadful news which I have just received from Longbourn.

09:38.300 --> 09:41.100
She burst into tears as she alluded to it,

09:41.260 --> 09:43.820
and for a few minutes could not speak another word.

09:44.900 --> 09:50.100
Darcy, in wretched suspense, could only say something indistinctly of his concern,

09:50.440 --> 09:53.020
and observe her in compassionate silence.

09:54.020 --> 09:56.080
At length she spoke again.

09:56.880 --> 10:00.820
I have just had a letter from Jane, with such dreadful news.

10:00.820 --> 10:03.000
It cannot be concealed from anyone.

10:03.800 --> 10:07.040
My youngest sister has left all her friends, has eloped,

10:07.660 --> 10:11.240
has thrown herself into the power of Mr Wickham.

10:11.700 --> 10:13.580
They are gone off together from Brighton.

10:14.000 --> 10:16.220
You know him too well to doubt the rest.

10:16.560 --> 10:20.380
She has no money, no connections, nothing that can tempt him to.

10:20.740 --> 10:22.200
She is lost forever.

10:23.560 --> 10:25.700
Darcy was fixed in astonishment.

10:26.920 --> 10:30.800
When I consider, she added in a yet more agitated voice,

10:30.820 --> 10:33.080
that I might have prevented it.

10:33.300 --> 10:35.220
I, who knew what he was.

10:35.740 --> 10:38.140
Had I but explained some part of it only,

10:38.400 --> 10:41.040
some part of what I learnt to my own family.

10:41.720 --> 10:44.380
Had his character been known, this could not have happened.

10:45.360 --> 10:47.760
But it is all too late now.

10:50.120 --> 10:55.060
I am grieved indeed, cried Darcy, grieved, shocked.

10:55.500 --> 10:58.080
But is it certain, absolutely certain?

10:58.720 --> 11:02.120
Oh yes, they left Brighton together on Sunday night,

11:02.160 --> 11:05.020
and were traced almost to London, but not beyond.

11:05.340 --> 11:07.120
They are certainly not gone to Scotland.

11:08.080 --> 11:09.200
And what has been done?

11:09.280 --> 11:11.380
What has been attempted to recover her?

11:12.340 --> 11:14.040
My father has gone to London,

11:14.320 --> 11:17.360
and Jane has written to beg my uncle's immediate assistance.

11:17.480 --> 11:20.340
And we shall be off, I hope, in half an hour.

11:20.760 --> 11:22.080
But nothing can be done.

11:22.260 --> 11:24.240
I know very well that nothing can be done.

11:24.540 --> 11:26.500
How is such a man to be worked on?

11:27.140 --> 11:29.080
How are they even to be discovered?

11:29.720 --> 11:31.580
I have not the smallest hope.

11:31.920 --> 11:33.520
It is every way horrible.

11:34.280 --> 11:37.340
Darcy shook his head in silent acquiescence.

11:40.480 --> 11:43.460
When my eyes were opened to his real character.

11:44.060 --> 11:47.800
Oh, had I known what I ought, what I dared to do.

11:48.080 --> 11:50.980
But I knew not, I was afraid of doing too much.

11:51.320 --> 11:53.180
Wretched, wretched mistake.

11:54.240 --> 11:55.880
Darcy made no answer.

11:55.880 --> 11:58.360
He seemed scarcely to hear her,

11:58.560 --> 12:01.840
and was walking up and down the room in earnest meditation,

12:02.220 --> 12:05.040
his brow contracted, his air gloomy.

12:05.980 --> 12:09.140
Elizabeth soon observed and instantly understood it.

12:09.560 --> 12:10.820
Her power was sinking.

12:11.580 --> 12:15.000
Everything must sink under such a proof of family weakness,

12:15.700 --> 12:17.900
such an assurance of the deepest disgrace.

12:18.680 --> 12:20.860
She could neither wonder nor condemn,

12:21.160 --> 12:23.220
but the belief of his self-conquest

12:23.220 --> 12:25.960
brought nothing consolatory to her bosom,

12:26.260 --> 12:28.620
afforded no palatation of her distress.

12:29.440 --> 12:32.640
It was, on the contrary, exactly calculated

12:32.640 --> 12:34.620
to make her understand her own wishes,

12:35.040 --> 12:38.320
and never had she so honestly felt that she could have loved him,

12:38.440 --> 12:41.000
as now, when all love must be vain.

12:42.200 --> 12:45.940
But self, though it would intrude, could not engross her.

12:46.420 --> 12:50.640
Lydia, the humiliation, the misery she was bringing on them all,

12:50.880 --> 12:53.120
soon swallowed up every private care.

12:53.780 --> 12:56.140
And covering her face with her handkerchief,

12:56.680 --> 12:58.800
Elizabeth was soon lost to everything else,

12:59.440 --> 13:01.980
and, after a pause of several minutes,

13:02.260 --> 13:04.820
was only recalled to a sense of her situation

13:04.820 --> 13:06.400
by the voice of her companion,

13:06.880 --> 13:09.720
who, in a manner which, though it spoke compassion,

13:10.260 --> 13:12.460
spoke likewise restraint, said,

13:13.160 --> 13:16.380
I am afraid you have been long desiring my absence,

13:16.700 --> 13:19.640
nor have I anything to plead an excuse of my stay,

13:19.940 --> 13:22.540
but a real, though unavailing concern.

13:22.540 --> 13:27.700
Would to heaven that anything could be either said or done on my part

13:27.700 --> 13:30.620
that might offer consolation to such distress.

13:31.740 --> 13:34.360
But I will torment you not with vain wishes,

13:34.620 --> 13:37.400
which may seem purposely to ask for your thanks.

13:38.140 --> 13:41.100
This unfortunate affair will, I fear,

13:41.760 --> 13:45.720
prevent my sisters having the pleasure of seeing her at Pemberley today.

13:46.640 --> 13:50.820
Oh yes, be so kind as to apologize for us to Miss Darcy.

13:50.820 --> 13:54.020
Say that urgent business calls us home immediately.

13:54.600 --> 13:57.680
Conceal the unhappy truth as long as it is possible.

13:58.160 --> 13:59.780
I know it cannot be long.

14:00.720 --> 14:03.020
He readily assured her of his secrecy,

14:03.720 --> 14:06.240
again expressed his sorrow for her distress,

14:06.980 --> 14:10.260
wished it a happier conclusion than there was at present reason to hope,

14:10.720 --> 14:13.200
and, leaving his compliments for her relations

14:13.200 --> 14:17.400
with only one serious parting look, went away.

14:18.540 --> 14:20.080
As he quitted the room,

14:20.080 --> 14:24.700
Elizabeth felt how improbable it was that they should ever see each other again

14:24.700 --> 14:29.340
on such terms of cordiality as had marked their several meetings in Derbyshire.

14:30.160 --> 14:33.840
And as she threw a retrospective glance over the whole of their acquaintance,

14:34.620 --> 14:36.920
so full of contradictions and varieties,

14:37.960 --> 14:40.340
sighed at the perseverance of those feelings

14:40.340 --> 14:43.440
which would now have promoted its continuance

14:43.440 --> 14:46.480
and would formally have rejoiced in its termination.

14:47.240 --> 14:51.100
If gratitude and esteem are good foundations of affection,

14:51.780 --> 14:55.820
Elizabeth's change of sentiment will be neither improbable nor faulty.

14:56.520 --> 15:02.380
But if otherwise, if regard springing from such sources is unreasonable or unnatural,

15:02.900 --> 15:05.380
in comparison of what is so often described

15:05.380 --> 15:08.080
as arising on a first interview with its object,

15:08.620 --> 15:11.440
and even before two words have been exchanged,

15:12.120 --> 15:13.940
nothing can be said in her defense,

15:13.940 --> 15:18.060
except that she had given somewhat of a trial to the latter method

15:18.060 --> 15:19.980
in her partiality for Wickham,

15:20.680 --> 15:23.500
and that its ill-success might, perhaps,

15:24.020 --> 15:27.700
authorize her to seek the other less interesting mode of attachment.

15:28.860 --> 15:31.820
Be that as it may, she saw him go with regret,

15:32.660 --> 15:36.540
and in this early example of what Lydia's infamy must produce,

15:37.240 --> 15:40.920
found additional anguish as she reflected on that wretched business.

15:41.480 --> 15:44.020
Never since reading Jane's second letter

15:44.020 --> 15:47.200
had she entertained a hope of Wickham's meaning to marry her.

15:47.720 --> 15:49.420
No one but Jane, she thought,

15:49.680 --> 15:51.960
could flatter herself with such an expectation.

15:53.100 --> 15:55.760
Surprise was the least of her feelings on this development.

15:56.660 --> 15:59.760
While the contents of the first letter remained in her mind,

16:00.180 --> 16:03.100
she was all surprise, all astonishment,

16:03.420 --> 16:07.320
that Wickham should marry a girl whom it was impossible he could marry for money,

16:07.800 --> 16:10.160
and how Lydia could ever have attached him

16:10.160 --> 16:11.980
had appeared incomprehensible.

16:12.680 --> 16:14.660
But now it was all too natural.

16:15.340 --> 16:18.980
For such an attachment as this, she might have sufficient charms,

16:19.520 --> 16:23.900
and though she did not suppose Lydia to be deliberately engaging in elopement

16:23.900 --> 16:25.480
without the intention of marriage,

16:25.940 --> 16:30.980
she had no difficulty in believing that neither her virtue nor her understanding

16:30.980 --> 16:33.940
would preserve her from falling an easy prey.

16:35.080 --> 16:38.740
She had never perceived, while the regiment was in Hertfordshire,

16:38.740 --> 16:41.680
that Lydia had any partiality for him,

16:42.060 --> 16:44.980
but she was convinced that Lydia wanted only encouragement

16:44.980 --> 16:46.740
to attach herself to anybody.

16:47.500 --> 16:49.940
Sometimes one officer, sometimes another,

16:50.340 --> 16:54.260
had been her favourite, as their attentions raised them in her opinion.

16:55.100 --> 16:59.540
Her affections had continually been fluctuating, but never without an object.

17:00.420 --> 17:03.960
The mischief of neglect and mistaken indulgence towards such a girl,

17:04.400 --> 17:07.140
oh, how acutely did she now feel it!

17:07.760 --> 17:11.700
She was wild to be at home, to hear, to see,

17:11.900 --> 17:16.980
to be upon the spot to share with Jane in the cares that must now fall wholly upon her.

17:17.420 --> 17:22.980
In a family so deranged, a father absent, a mother incapable of exertion

17:22.980 --> 17:24.940
and requiring constant attendance,

17:25.480 --> 17:28.600
and though almost persuaded that nothing could be done for Lydia,

17:29.060 --> 17:32.140
her uncle's interference seemed of the utmost importance.

17:32.560 --> 17:35.380
Until he entered the room, her impatience was severe.

17:36.020 --> 17:38.860
Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner had hurried back in alarm,

17:39.400 --> 17:43.380
supposing by the servants' account that their niece was taken suddenly ill.

17:44.000 --> 17:46.460
But satisfying them instantly on that head,

17:46.780 --> 17:49.820
she eagerly communicated the calls of their summons,

17:49.960 --> 17:55.240
reading the two letters aloud and dwelling on the postscript of the last with trembling energy.

17:55.580 --> 17:57.800
Though Lydia had never been a favourite with them,

17:58.060 --> 18:00.980
Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner could not but be deeply afflicted.

18:01.880 --> 18:05.240
Not Lydia only, but all were concerned in it,

18:05.480 --> 18:08.800
and after the first exclamations of surprise and horror,

18:09.240 --> 18:12.100
Mr. Gardiner promised every assistance in his power.

18:13.020 --> 18:17.160
Elizabeth, though expecting no less, thanked him with tears of gratitude,

18:17.660 --> 18:20.340
and all three being actuated by one spirit,

18:20.840 --> 18:23.580
everything relating to their journey was speedily settled.

18:24.140 --> 18:26.160
They were to be off as soon as possible.

18:27.280 --> 18:31.320
"'But what is to be done about Pemberley?' cried Mrs. Gardiner.

18:31.800 --> 18:35.940
"'John told us Mr. Darcy was here when you sent for us. Was it so?'

18:37.020 --> 18:41.440
"'Yes, and I told him we should not be able to keep our engagement. That is all settled.'

18:43.100 --> 18:47.560
"'What is all settled?' repeated the other as she ran into the room to prepare.

18:48.260 --> 18:52.160
"'And are they upon such terms as for her to disclose the real truth?'

18:52.740 --> 18:56.860
"'Oh, that I knew how it was.' But wishes were vain,

18:57.280 --> 19:01.860
or at least could only serve to amuse her in the hurry and confusion of the following hour.

19:02.820 --> 19:07.340
Had Elizabeth been at leisure to be idle, she would have remained certain that all employment

19:07.340 --> 19:13.580
was impossible to one so wretched as herself. But she had her share of business as well as her aunt,

19:14.140 --> 19:18.540
and amongst the rest there were notes to be written to all their friends at Lambden,

19:18.900 --> 19:21.400
with false excuses for their sudden departure.

19:22.260 --> 19:26.600
An hour, however, saw the whole complete it, and Mr. Gardiner,

19:26.820 --> 19:31.380
meanwhile having settled his account at the inn, nothing remained to be done but to go.

19:31.720 --> 19:37.100
And Elizabeth, after all the misery of the morning, found herself, in a shorter space

19:37.100 --> 19:42.160
of time than she could have supposed, seated in the carriage and on the road to Longbourn.

